  "name": "Nagaraja COU1 — Non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending credibility assessment (Minimal profile)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for FEA prediction of ASTM F1717 static compression-bending performance of a non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct evaluated under simulated lumbar fusion loading conditions. The FEA model ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) is compared against N=11 experimental constructs across two independent laboratories. All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed. The intended use is to support 510(k) submission for a Class II spinal fixation system; the model is used to predict construct stiffness and failure load within the ASTM F1717 test envelope. One factor (Test conditions) is below the required credibility level owing to a single test condition being exercised.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/nagaraja-f1717-compression-bending-req-001",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/nagaraja-fea-predicts-f1717-stiffness-failure-load",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/nagaraja-pedicle-screw-fea-ensemble-v3",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-f1717-experimental-n11-lab1",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-f1717-experimental-n11-lab2"
  ],
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/nagaraja-f1717-stiffness-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "ASTM F1717 construct stiffness — FEA vs. experiment comparison (N=11, two labs)"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/nagaraja-f1717-failure-load-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "ASTM F1717 failure load — FEA vs. experiment comparison (N=11, two labs)"
    }
  ],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2024",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Overall credibility is assessed as Medium. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors meet or exceed required levels. The single shortfall in Test conditions (achieved level 1, required level 2) is offset by high confidence in model form, numerical verification, and cross-laboratory experimental consistency. The assessment team accepts the model for the stated 510(k) submission purpose under the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw ASTM F1717 compression-bending scenario.",
    "decidedAt": "2024-11-15T00:00:00Z"
  },
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1) is validated under an ISO 9001-compliant QMS with documented version control, regression test suite, and release notes.",
      "rationale": "DePuy Synthes and FDA both employ Ansys Mechanical under ISO 9001-certified QMS environments. Regression test suites covering linear static and contact-nonlinear analyses are executed at each release. Version 2023 R1 was used throughout; no defects relevant to contact or large-deformation analysis were open at time of study."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks from ASME V&V 10 and Ansys published verification manual cover the element types and contact formulations employed.",
      "rationale": "Ansys publishes an extensive verification manual; benchmark problems covering SOLID186, CONTA174/TARGE170 contact pairs, and augmented Lagrangian formulations were reviewed. All benchmark results reproduced to within 0.5% of analytical solutions. Additional in-house patch tests were executed confirming correct rigid-body and constant-strain response."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QOI (stiffness, peak von Mises stress at screw-rod interface) changes by less than 5% between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities were evaluated (coarse ~120k elements, medium ~380k elements, fine ~950k elements). Richardson extrapolation yielded a grid convergence index of 1.8% for stiffness and 3.2% for peak stress at the screw-rod interface. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force and displacement residuals converge to below 1e-4 relative tolerance; energy criterion satisfied at each load step.",
      "rationale": "Sparse direct solver (SPARSE) employed with double-precision arithmetic. Force residual norm converged below 1e-5 and displacement residual below 1e-4 at every load step across all 11 model instances. No non-convergence events were recorded. Energy balance checked post-solution; artificial energy (hourglass) was zero for fully integrated elements used."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with peer review of model setup; independent analyst verification of boundary conditions and material assignments.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation protocol specifying boundary condition application, material property assignment, and contact definition was followed. An independent analyst (FDA reviewer) repeated the model setup from the protocol and obtained stiffness predictions within 1.3% of the primary analyst results, confirming absence of systematic use error."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear-elastic model with frictional contact at screw-rod interface is appropriate for ASTM F1717 sub-yield loading; justified by literature and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 protocol loads constructs to 50% of failure load for stiffness measurement; strains remain elastic. A linear-elastic continuum model with Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) and Coulomb friction (μ=0.25) at the screw-rod polyaxial interface captures the dominant load path. Sensitivity analysis showed ±20% variation in friction coefficient produced less than 4% change in predicted stiffness, supporting model form adequacy."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for the specific lot; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio) were taken from certified material test reports for the Ti-6Al-4V lot used in fabrication. Screw and rod geometry was measured by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) on three representative specimens; mean dimensions used in the nominal model with ±1σ dimensional variation explored in sensitivity runs. Input uncertainty contributed less than 2% variation in QOIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 experimental specimens from production lots tested across two independent laboratories; specimens traceable to device design history file.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-equivalent components and tested across two independent laboratories (Lab A: n=6, Lab B: n=5). All specimens were traceable to the device design history file. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2%, confirming adequate sample representativeness."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least two distinct loading configurations (e.g., different rod lengths or offset distances) exercised to span the intended use envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717-prescribed configuration (35 mm offset, standard rod length). While this configuration is the regulatory standard, it represents only one point in the construct design space. The required level of 2 was not achieved because no additional configurations were tested. This shortfall is acknowledged and accepted given the regulatory precedent of the F1717 standard."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably match experimental specimen parameters within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "CMM measurements of test specimens were used directly to parameterize the FEA models. Material certificates confirmed elastic modulus within 2% of nominal. Boundary conditions replicated the F1717 fixture constraints: fixed inferior block, axial compressive load applied at superior block with 35 mm anterior offset. Torque applied to set screw was measured and translated to equivalent contact preload in the model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted stiffness and failure load lie within ±15% of experimental mean; statistical comparison using t-test or equivalence test reported.",
      "rationale": "Mean predicted stiffness: 142 N/mm (FEA) vs. 138 N/mm (experiment, mean); relative error 2.9%. Mean predicted failure load: 1,820 N (FEA) vs. 1,795 N (experiment, mean); relative error 1.4%. All FEA predictions fell within the experimental 95% confidence interval. A two one-sided t-test (TOST) confirmed equivalence within ±15% bounds (p<0.01)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QOIs (construct stiffness, failure load) are directly linked to the clinical performance claim and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and failure load under ASTM F1717 compression-bending are the primary regulatory QOIs for 510(k) submission of spinal fixation systems. These quantities directly characterize the mechanical performance relevant to the clinical claim of adequate fixation under physiological lumbar loading. No surrogate QOIs are used."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw) matches the intended use scenario in device type, loading mode, and regulatory context.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the regulatory test method (ASTM F1717) for the specific device configuration (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, titanium alloy rod) under the loading mode (static compression-bending) relevant to the 510(k) submission. The experimental and simulation scenarios are congruent in device, loading, and regulatory framing, providing high relevance of the validation activity to the intended use."
    }
  ],
